1 Introduction

For each instance, several parameters describe the network topology, complexity, and resources (Table 1.1).

Table 1.1: Instance topology, complexity, and resource parameters.
Network Topology
nbAct Number of activities
CNC Coefficient of Network Complexity
OS Order Strength
SP Serial-Parallel Network Indicator
AD Activity distribution Indicator
LA Length arcs indicator
I5 I5 indicator
TF Total float indicator
Complexity indictors
Wprec Network width (maximal number of activities in parallel in the network), called W in the original study
Wall Instance width (maximal number of activities in parallel considering precedence relations and resource restrictions) (Extension of Wprec, not proposed in any study)
NA General info of the next 4 lines: Feasible sets FS<x><u> indicator denotingthe feasible subsets of <x> normalized by combinations of <x> (in case <u>=1) or by feasible subsets considering only the network (in case <u>=2).
FS21 FS_1^2 indicator
FS22 FS_2^2 indicator
FS31 FS_1^3 indicator
FS32 FS_2^3 indicator
l Number of linear extentions [not available for all instances; n.f. - not found ] necessary to calculate LE (Equation (4) in the study)
f The number of maximal feasible extentions [not available for all instances; n.f. - not found]
LE Linear extentions indicator (depend on l)
FE Feasible extentions indicator (depend on f)
Resource parameters
nbR Number of resources
RF Resource factor
RU Resource use
RS Resource strength
RC Resource constraintness
nblR Number of resources in lowRU instance version
lRF RF for lowRU instance
lRU RU for lowRU instance
lRS RS for lowRU instance
lRC RC for lowRU instance
nbhR Number of resources in highRD instance version
hRF RF for highRD instance
hRU RU for highRD instance
hRS RS for highRD instance
hRC RC for highRD instance

2 Results

2.1 CV dataset

The Coelho-Vanhoucke (CV) dataset consists of 623 RCPSP instances, first described in Coelho and Vanhoucke (2020) that can be downloaded from here. Figure 2.1 shows the correlation between different parameters (Table 1.1) in all 623 instances. Figure @ref(fig: cv-cormat-reorder) shows the same correlation with the rows and column reordered to show highly correlated hierarchical clusters.

As of September 2023, three different authors have submitted their run-time results and best (or optimal) solution to each of the instances; - Coelho and Vanhoucke (2020) designed this dataset with difficult to solve instances and provided their solutions to some of them. - Watermeyer and Zimmermann (2022) was the first one to add further solutions to improve upon the already achieved results. - Creemers (2021) recently added his results and is able to solve almost all instances.

In this chapter, we compare the run times reported by each of the researchers for each of the instances. If a researcher is unable to find the optimal solution (within a certain time limit), they might still report the best solution that was found.

Figure 2.1: Correlation between the different numeric parameters of interest.

Figure 2.2: Correlation between the different numeric parameters of interest (hierarchical clustering reordering).

2.1.1 Run times: Kaplan Meier

In this chapter, we look at the different run times to find an optimal solution. If an optimal solution is not found, a lower bound and/or heuristic solution was reported instead. If a non-optimal solution is reported, we consider the run time to be right-censored.

Figure 2.3 shows the run times for different authors. It can be seen than Coelho and Vanhoucke (2020) solves none of the instances to optimality. They designed this dataset to be difficult such that it can serve as a benchmarking dataset for new RCPSP algorithms. Watermeyer and Zimmermann (2022) can solve almost 30% of all instances to optimality. Since they stop their algorithm after 3600 seconds, all other instances are right censored at that time. Lastly, Creemers (2021) allows for a maximum run time of 48 hours. If no optimal solution is found after that, the instance is right-censored.

Table 2.1 shows different quantiles for each author with log-log 95% confidence intervals.

Figure 2.3: Comparing the run time for the different authors.

Table 2.1: Quantiles and confidence intervals for the time to solve to optimality.
author q90 q75 q50 q25 q10
CV Inf, [Inf, Inf] Inf, [Inf, Inf] Inf, [Inf, Inf] Inf, [Inf, Inf] Inf, [Inf, Inf]
WZ 614162, [426204, 801512] 3129820, [2137160, Inf] Inf, [Inf, Inf] Inf, [Inf, Inf] Inf, [Inf, Inf]
C 6123, [2093, 7873] 30992, [22463, 47960] 212940, [171057, 245239] 1297992, [818495, 1793611] 8344589, [5605280, 12018995]

2.1.2 Runtime with different instance parameters

2.1.2.1 Analysis of the Nbact parameter

The nbAct parameter takes values between 20 and 30. nbAct is defined as Number of activities. It is split up in 3 equal-sized discrete bins (same number of instances in each bin). We now compare the run times for instances in each of the 3 bins for both Watermeyer and Zimmermann (2022) and Creemers (2021).

Figure 2.4 shows the different Kaplan- Meier curves.

Figure 2.4: Comparing the run time for WZ (left) and C (right). Note that the x-axis does not match
